00:22:52,326 --> 00:22:56,490
Sammy was my first real challenge.

247
00:22:56,563 --> 00:22:59,088
[Engine Starts]

248
00:23:01,001 --> 00:23:04,402
Yo, Lenny! I thought you split for good.

249
00:23:04,471 --> 00:23:07,770
- Well, things change. - So I see.

250
00:23:07,841 --> 00:23:10,935
- My name's Teddy. - I guess I've told you about my condition.

251
00:23:11,011 --> 00:23:15,004
Only every time I see you. Come on, I'll buy you lunch.

252
00:23:20,654 --> 00:23:22,918
- Have I told you about Sammy Jankis? - Mm. Yeah.

253
00:23:22,990 --> 00:23:26,289
I'm sick of hearing about the guy. What about John G?

254
00:23:26,360 --> 00:23:29,852
- Who? - Johnny G., the guy you're looking for.

255
00:23:29,930 --> 00:23:32,524
- That's why you haven't left town, am I right? - Maybe.

256
00:23:32,599 --> 00:23:35,932
- Leonard, look, you have to be very careful. - Why?

257
00:23:36,003 --> 00:23:38,301
The other day you mentioned that maybe somebody...

258
00:23:38,372 --> 00:23:40,772
was trying to set you up, get you to kill the wrong guy.

259
00:23:40,841 --> 00:23:44,436
Well, I go on facts, not recommendations, but thank you.

260
00:23:44,511 --> 00:23:47,537
Lenny, you can't trust a man's life to your little notes and pictures.

261
00:23:47,614 --> 00:23:50,447
- Why not? - Because your notes could be unreliable.

262
00:23:50,517 --> 00:23:52,610
- Memory's unreliable. - Oh, please!

263
00:23:52,686 --> 00:23:55,621
No, really. Memory's not perfect. It's not even that good.

264
00:23:55,689 --> 00:23:58,624
Ask the police. Eyewitness testimony is unreliable.

265
00:23:58,692 --> 00:24:01,752
- Cops don't catch a killer by remembering stuff. - Right...

266
00:24:01,828 --> 00:24:04,991
They collect facts, they make notes, and they draw conclusions.

267
00:24:05,065 --> 00:24:08,831
Facts, not memories. That's how you investigate. It's what I used to do.

268
00:24:08,902 --> 00:24:13,100
Look, memory can change the shape of a room. It can change the color of a car.

269
00:24:13,173 --> 00:24:15,266
And memories can be distorted.

270
00:24:15,342 --> 00:24:17,537
They're just an interpretation. They're not a record.

271
00:24:17,611 --> 00:24:19,670
They're irrelevant if you have the facts.

272
00:24:19,746 --> 00:24:22,510
You really want to get this guy, don't you?

273
00:24:22,583 --> 00:24:26,383
He killed my wife. He took away my fucking memory.

274
00:24:28,288 --> 00:24:30,882
He destroyed my ability to live.

275
00:24:33,594 --> 00:24:38,031
- You're living. - Only for revenge.

276
00:24:38,098 --> 00:24:40,396
Well, then we'll get the bastard.

277
00:24:40,467 --> 00:24:43,163
Where are you staying?

278
00:24:43,237 --> 00:24:46,206
The Discount Inn.

279
00:24:48,108 --> 00:24:49,871
I don't know what room. I haven't got my key.

280
00:24:49,943 --> 00:24:51,934
Probably left in in your room.

281
00:25:03,257 --> 00:25:05,919
[Bell Ringing]

282
00:25:05,993 --> 00:25:09,485
Hi. I'm checked in here, but I think I've misplaced my key.

283
00:25:09,563 --> 00:25:13,863
How you doing, Leonard? Probably in the room, right?

284
00:25:32,519 --> 00:25:34,111
I don't see my key anywhere.

285
00:25:34,187 --> 00:25:36,280
This is the wrong room. You're in 304 now.

286
00:25:36,356 --> 00:25:38,881
- I'm sorry. I fucked up. - This is not my room?

287
00:25:38,959 --> 00:25:41,894
- No. Come on, let's go. - Why is this my handwriting?

288
00:25:45,632 --> 00:25:50,001
Well... this was your room, but now you're in 304.

289
00:25:50,070 --> 00:25:52,334
- When was I in here? - Last week.

290
00:25:52,406 --> 00:25:55,842
- But then I rented you another room on top of it. - Why?

291
00:25:55,909 --> 00:25:59,242
Business is slow. I mean, I told my boss about the...

292
00:25:59,313 --> 00:26:02,339
your condition and stuff, and he said try and rent him another room.

293
00:26:02,416 --> 00:26:05,783
So how many rooms am I checked into in this shit-hole?

294
00:26:05,852 --> 00:26:08,082
Just two, so far.

295
00:26:08,155 --> 00:26:11,386
Well, at least you're being honest about ripping me off.

296
00:26:11,458 --> 00:26:13,722
Well, you're not gonna remember anyway.

297
00:26:13,794 --> 00:26:15,853
You don't have to be that honest, Burt.

298
00:26:15,929 --> 00:26:19,126
Leonard, always get a receipt.

299
00:26:19,199 --> 00:26:21,429
Oh, yeah. I'm gonna write that down.

300
00:26:23,870 --> 00:26:26,703
- Hey, what time is it? - Quarter to one.

301
00:26:26,773 --> 00:26:28,707
Excuse me.

302
00:26:28,775 --> 00:26:30,709
Your room's...

303
00:26:43,490 --> 00:26:45,549
- Natalie? - You don't remember me.

304
00:26:45,625 --> 00:26:48,822
I'd just become an investigator when I came across Sammy.

305
00:26:48,895 --> 00:26:52,626
Mr. Samuel R. Jankis. Strangest case ever.

306
00:26:52,699 --> 00:26:55,224
Now, the guy's a 58-year-old semiretired accountant.

307
00:26:55,302 --> 00:26:58,237
He and his wife had been in this car accident. Nothing too serious.

308
00:26:58,305 --> 00:27:01,468
But he's acting funny. He can't get a handle on what's going on.

309
00:27:02,976 --> 00:27:06,673
The doctors find some possible damage to the hippocampus.

310
00:27:06,747 --> 00:27:10,410
Nothing conclusive, but Sammy can't remember anything for more than a couple of minutes.

311
00:27:10,484 --> 00:27:13,248
Can't work, can't do shit. The medical bills pile up.

312
00:27:13,320 --> 00:27:16,756
His wife calls the insurance company, and I get sent in.

313
00:27:16,823 --> 00:27:21,590
Now, this is my first big claims investigation, so I really check into it.

314
00:27:21,661 --> 00:27:24,425
- Can I get you some coffee? - Sammy can think just fine,

315
00:27:24,498 --> 00:27:26,898
but he can't make any new memories.

316
00:27:26,967 --> 00:27:29,595
- He can only remember things for a couple of minutes. - This is Mr. Shelby.

317
00:27:29,669 --> 00:27:32,934
He'd watch TV, but anything longer than a couple of minutes was too confusing.

318
00:27:33,006 --> 00:27:35,702
He couldn't remember how it began. He liked commercials.

319
00:27:35,776 --> 00:27:37,539
- They were short. - Sammy.

320
00:27:37,611 --> 00:27:39,545
It's time for my shot.

321
00:27:39,613 --> 00:27:41,672
The crazy part was that this guy...

322
00:27:41,748 --> 00:27:45,275
who couldn't even follow the plot of Green Acres anymore...

323
00:27:45,352 --> 00:27:48,446
could do the most complicated things...

324
00:27:48,522 --> 00:27:52,185
as long as he learned them before the accident...

325
00:27:52,259 --> 00:27:54,523
and as long as he kept his mind on what he was doing.

326
00:27:54,594 --> 00:27:58,428
- Be gentle. - Now, the doctors assure me...

327
00:27:58,498 --> 00:28:02,525
there's a real condition called anterial-grade memory loss, or short-term memory loss.

328
00:28:02,602 --> 00:28:04,866
It's rare, but legit.

329
00:28:06,606 --> 00:28:09,336
Every time I see him...

330
00:28:09,409 --> 00:28:11,877
I catch this look,

331
00:28:11,945 --> 00:28:15,039
this slight look of recognition.

332
00:28:15,115 --> 00:28:17,447
But he says he can't remember me at all.

333
00:28:17,517 --> 00:28:20,543
Sammy, it's okay. I got it. I got it.

334
00:28:20,620 --> 00:28:23,088
- Hi, Mr. Shelby. - Hi, Mrs. Jankis.

335
00:28:23,156 --> 00:28:27,752
- Now, I can read people, and I'm thinking: Bad actor. - This is Mr. Shelby, Sammy.

336
00:28:27,828 --> 00:28:30,729
So now I'm suspicious, and I order more tests.

337
00:28:33,900 --> 00:28:37,131
[Thinking] Awake.

338
00:28:37,204 --> 00:28:40,002
Oh, where am I?

339
00:28:42,042 --> 00:28:44,636
Somebody's bedroom.

340
00:28:46,346 --> 00:28:48,814
Ah, it must be her room.

341
00:28:48,882 --> 00:28:51,407
But who is she?

342
00:28:54,855 --> 00:28:57,551
[Moaning]

343
00:28:59,693 --> 00:29:01,627
It's only me.

344
00:29:03,897 --> 00:29:06,866
- Did you sleep okay? - Yeah. You?

345
00:29:06,933 --> 00:29:12,337
Yeah. Oh, shit. Shit! I got to be someplace.

346
00:29:16,209 --> 00:29:20,305
- It's pretty weird. - It's useful.

347
00:29:20,380 --> 00:29:22,974
You never write a phone number on your hand?

348
00:29:23,049 --> 00:29:28,385
I, um... I should be able to talk to my friend today about the license plate.

349
00:29:28,455 --> 00:29:32,892
- Yeah, the license plate. - John G.'s license plate.

350
00:29:35,262 --> 00:29:37,457
You have it tattooed on your thigh.

351
00:29:48,308 --> 00:29:51,471
[Water Running]

352
00:29:55,148 --> 00:29:57,275
[Thinking] "Natalie."

353
00:29:59,886 --> 00:30:01,854
"She has also lost someone.

354
00:30:01,922 --> 00:30:03,890
She will help you out of pity."

355
00:30:05,759 --> 00:30:08,057
[Footsteps]

356
00:30:08,128 --> 00:30:11,120
Mm, if it's registered in this state,

357
00:30:11,197 --> 00:30:14,462
it should only take a couple of seconds to pull up his license and registration.

358
00:30:14,534 --> 00:30:17,025
I'll call you as soon as I talk to him.

359
00:30:17,103 --> 00:30:20,937
Do you think we could just arrange a meeting now? I'm not too good on the phone.

360
00:30:27,414 --> 00:30:31,282
You know, it's great that you...

361
00:30:31,351 --> 00:30:36,288
well, that you're helping me like this.

362
00:30:36,356 --> 00:30:39,848
I'm helping you because you helped me.

363
00:30:51,972 --> 00:30:55,874
So next time you see me, will you remember me?

364
00:31:12,926 --> 00:31:15,417
[Whispering] I think you will.

365
00:31:15,495 --> 00:31:18,328
I'm sorry.

366
00:31:20,634 --> 00:31:24,263
Lenny, before you go, could I have my shirt back, please?

367
00:31:34,848 --> 00:31:37,544
[Engine Starts]

368
00:31:39,586 --> 00:31:43,522
Yo, Lenny! I thought you split for good.

369
00:31:43,590 --> 00:31:46,559
Sammy couldn't pick up any new skills at all.

370
00:31:46,626 --> 00:31:50,392
But I find something in my research: Conditioning.

371
00:31:50,463 --> 00:31:53,591
Sammy should still be able to learn through repetition.

372
00:31:53,667 --> 00:31:56,568
It's how you learn stuff like riding a bike. You just get better through practice.

373
00:31:56,636 --> 00:31:59,605
It's a completely different part of the brain from the short-term memory.

374
00:31:59,673 --> 00:32:03,268
So I had the doctors test Sammy's response to conditioning.

375
00:32:03,343 --> 00:32:07,245
- Just pick up any three objects. - That's a test?

376
00:32:07,313 --> 00:32:09,941
Hey, where were you guys when I did my C.P. A?

377
00:32:10,016 --> 00:32:12,143
[Laughs] Sorry.

378
00:32:13,586 --> 00:32:15,315
Ta-da!

379
00:32:15,388 --> 00:32:17,982
- [Object Buzzes] - Ow! What the fuck?

380
00:32:18,058 --> 00:32:21,789
- It's a test, Sammy. - Well, test this, you fucking quack.

381
00:32:21,861 --> 00:32:24,762
[Leonard] Some of the objects were electrified.

382
00:32:24,831 --> 00:32:27,732
They'd give him a small shock. They kept repeating the test,

383
00:32:27,801 --> 00:32:29,962
always with the same objects electrified.

384
00:32:30,036 --> 00:32:33,267
The point was to see if Sammy could learn to avoid the electrified objects...

385
00:32:33,339 --> 00:32:35,603
not by memory, but by instinct.

386
00:32:44,384 --> 00:32:46,545
[Car Alarm Chirps]

387
00:32:50,623 --> 00:32:53,751
[Knocking]

388
00:32:55,995 --> 00:32:58,725
Natalie, right? Who the fuck is Dodd?

389
00:33:01,167 --> 00:33:03,897
Guess I don't have to worry about him anymore.

390
00:33:03,970 --> 00:33:06,962
- What the fuck have you got me into? - Shh. Come inside.

391
00:33:10,243 --> 00:33:13,212
- Who is he? - Calm down. Okay?

392
00:33:13,279 --> 00:33:16,771
This is my problem. It has nothing to do with your investigation.

393
00:33:16,850 --> 00:33:20,513
- How did you get me into this? - You offered to help when you saw what he did to my face.

394
00:33:20,587 --> 00:33:24,387
- How do I know he did that? - Because I came straight to you after he did it.

395
00:33:24,457 --> 00:33:28,393
- I showed you what he did, and I asked you to help me. - And I just take your word?

396
00:33:28,461 --> 00:33:32,192
- Yeah. - Something doesn't feel right.

397
00:33:32,265 --> 00:33:35,257
I think someone's fucking with me, trying to get me to kill the wrong guy.

398
00:33:35,335 --> 00:33:38,065
- Did you? Kill him? - What? Of course not!

399
00:33:38,138 --> 00:33:41,574
Hey, what... Sit down, okay? Sit.

400
00:33:41,641 --> 00:33:45,509
This has nothing to do with you.

401
00:33:45,578 --> 00:33:48,843
You helped me out, and I'm grateful.

402
00:33:48,915 --> 00:33:50,746
You have to burn them.

403
00:33:53,186 --> 00:33:56,383
Leonard, you decided to help me. Trust yourself.

404
00:33:56,456 --> 00:33:59,220
Trust your own judgment. You can question everything.

405
00:33:59,292 --> 00:34:02,284
- You can never know anything for sure. - There are things you know for sure.

406
00:34:02,362 --> 00:34:04,489
Such as?

407
00:34:04,564 --> 00:34:07,795
I know what that's gonna sound like when I knock on it. [Knocks On Wood]

408
00:34:07,867 --> 00:34:10,961
I know what that's gonna feel like when I pick it up.

409
00:34:11,037 --> 00:34:14,598
See? Certainties. It's the kind of memory you take for granted.

410
00:34:16,142 --> 00:34:19,134
You know, I can remember so much.

411
00:34:20,647 --> 00:34:24,811
The feel of the world... and her.

412
00:34:24,884 --> 00:34:27,944
[Sighing]

413
00:34:28,021 --> 00:34:32,355
She's gone.

414
00:34:32,425 --> 00:34:36,327
And the present is trivia, which I scribble down as fucking notes!

415
00:34:36,396 --> 00:34:39,422
Hey, hey, come on. Try and relax. Come on.

416
00:34:39,499 --> 00:34:42,525
It's not easy for me to relax, you know? Shh.

417
00:34:42,602 --> 00:34:45,093
Come on. Take your jacket off.

418
00:34:45,171 --> 00:34:48,470
Yeah. Come on.

419
00:34:48,541 --> 00:34:50,771
Here.

420
00:34:50,844 --> 00:34:55,110
Didn't think you were the type.

421
00:35:02,055 --> 00:35:04,649
It's backwards.

422
00:35:04,724 --> 00:35:08,182
Come here. Come here!

423
00:35:29,115 --> 00:35:32,107
What about here?

424
00:35:32,185 --> 00:35:35,848
Maybe it's for when I find him.

425
00:35:38,625 --> 00:35:41,025
I've lost somebody too.

426
00:35:42,528 --> 00:35:44,462
I'm sorry.

427
00:35:44,530 --> 00:35:46,760
His name was Jimmy.

428
00:35:46,833 --> 00:35:48,926
What happened to him?

429
00:35:49,002 --> 00:35:52,199
He went to meet somebody. He never came back.

430
00:35:52,272 --> 00:35:54,570
Who did he go to meet?

431
00:35:54,641 --> 00:35:56,905
A guy called Teddy.

432
00:35:56,976 --> 00:35:58,967
What do the police think?

433
00:35:59,045 --> 00:36:01,946
They don't look too hard for guys like Jimmy.

434
00:36:03,616 --> 00:36:07,552
When you find this guy, this John G.,

435
00:36:07,620 --> 00:36:09,713
what are you gonna do?

436
00:36:12,125 --> 00:36:14,286
I'm gonna kill him.

437
00:36:15,828 --> 00:36:18,353
Maybe I can help you find him.

438
00:36:22,869 --> 00:36:25,861
I don't even know how long she's been gone.

439
00:36:29,742 --> 00:36:33,644
It's like I've woken up in bed and she's not here...

440
00:36:35,214 --> 00:36:38,445
because she's gone to the bathroom or something.

441
00:36:42,588 --> 00:36:45,352
But somehow I just...

442
00:36:45,425 --> 00:36:48,724
I just know she's never gonna come back to bed.

443
00:36:54,267 --> 00:36:57,202
If I could just reach over...

444
00:36:57,270 --> 00:37:00,671
and touch her side of the bed...

445
00:37:00,740 --> 00:37:03,800
I would know that it was cold.

446
00:37:06,746 --> 00:37:08,714
But I can't.

447
00:37:13,186 --> 00:37:15,620
I know I can't have her back.

448
00:37:15,688 --> 00:37:20,352
But I don't want to wake up in the morning thinking she's still here.

449
00:37:21,894 --> 00:37:26,263
I lie here not knowing how long I've been alone.

450
00:37:32,538 --> 00:37:34,768
So how...

451
00:37:34,841 --> 00:37:37,105
How can I heal?

452
00:37:39,579 --> 00:37:44,642
How am I supposed to heal if I can't... feel time?

453
00:38:57,186 --> 00:39:00,246
[Thinking] "She has also lost someone.

454
00:39:00,323 --> 00:39:02,689
She will help you out of pity."

455
00:39:26,783 --> 00:39:29,980
They kept testing Sammy for months,

456
00:39:30,052 --> 00:39:33,044
always with the same objects carrying an electrical charge.

457
00:39:33,122 --> 00:39:35,215
- [Object Buzzes] - Ow! What the fuck?

458
00:39:35,291 --> 00:39:37,725
- It's a test, Sammy. - Test this, you quack!

459
00:39:37,794 --> 00:39:40,490
Even with total short-term memory loss,

460
00:39:40,563 --> 00:39:43,327
Sammy should have learned to instinctively stop picking up the wrong objects.

461
00:39:43,399 --> 00:39:47,460
All the previous cases responded to conditioning. Sammy didn't respond at all.

462
00:39:47,537 --> 00:39:51,132
It was enough to suggest that his condition was psychological, not physical.

463
00:39:51,207 --> 00:39:55,576
We turned down his claim on the grounds that he wasn't covered for mental illness.

464
00:39:55,645 --> 00:39:59,581
His wife got stuck with the bills, and I got a big promotion.

465
00:39:59,649 --> 00:40:03,847
Conditioning didn't work for Sammy, so he became helpless.

466
00:40:03,920 --> 00:40:07,981
But it works for me. I live the way Sammy couldn't.

467
00:40:08,057 --> 00:40:10,821
Habit and routine make my life possible.

468
00:40:10,893 --> 00:40:13,828
Conditioning. Acting on instinct.

469
00:40:15,898 --> 00:40:19,698
[Indistinct Screeching]

470
00:40:19,769 --> 00:40:21,999
[Man Shouts]

471
00:40:22,071 --> 00:40:24,835
- [Thinking] Awake. - [Car Horn Honks]

472
00:40:24,907 --> 00:40:27,068
Where am I?

473
00:40:28,744 --> 00:40:30,837
Motel room.

474
00:40:30,913 --> 00:40:33,381
[Groans]

475
00:40:36,886 --> 00:40:39,411
Some anonymous motel room.

476
00:40:42,925 --> 00:40:46,361
Nothing in the drawers, but I'll take a look anyway.

477
00:40:46,429 --> 00:40:50,798
Nothing except the Gideon Bi... Bible.

478
00:41:03,779 --> 00:41:07,442
[Knocking At Door] Hey, open up!

479
00:41:07,516 --> 00:41:10,451
- [Muffled Crying] - Just a minute.

480
00:41:10,519 --> 00:41:13,716
- Open the door. - [Continues Knocking]

481
00:41:13,789 --> 00:41:15,848
Lenny!

482
00:41:17,660 --> 00:41:20,060
Open the door!

483
00:41:23,366 --> 00:41:25,300
Come on!

484
00:41:26,502 --> 00:41:28,436
Hi, Teddy.

485
00:41:28,504 --> 00:41:31,132
- Finished playing with yourself, Lenny? - [Door Closes]

486
00:41:31,207 --> 00:41:33,937
- [Groans] - [Muffled Cries Continue]

487
00:41:38,447 --> 00:41:42,247
[Sighs]

488
00:41:42,318 --> 00:41:46,379
Oh, I get it. Amorous neighbors.

489
00:41:46,455 --> 00:41:48,923
- What are you doing here? - [Laughs]

490
00:41:48,991 --> 00:41:51,721
You called me. You said you needed my help.

